# Advanced Graph Algorithms in Java

Once you can navigate a graph (BFS/DFS), the next leap is answering *weighted* questions: 'What is the cheapest route?' and *ordering* questions: 'What tasks must come before others?' These algorithms each solve a specific shape of problem — understanding WHEN to use each is as important as HOW to implement it.

## Dijkstra — cheapest path from one source
```java
// Mental model: you're expanding a 'settled frontier' outward.
// At each step, pick the UNSETTLED node with the cheapest known distance
// (greedy). A min-heap makes this O((V+E) log V).
//
// Key invariant: once a node is polled from the heap, its distance is FINAL.
// This is why Dijkstra fails with NEGATIVE weights — a future negative edge
// could improve an already-settled distance.
//
int[] dijkstra(List<List<int[]>> adj, int src, int n) {
    int[] dist = new int[n];
    Arrays.fill(dist, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
    dist[src] = 0;
    // heap entry: [distance, node]
    PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.comparingInt(a -> a[0]));
    pq.offer(new int[]{0, src});
    while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
        int[] cur = pq.poll();
        int d = cur[0], u = cur[1];
        if (d > dist[u]) continue;  // stale entry — skip
        for (int[] edge : adj.get(u)) {
            int v = edge[0], w = edge[1];
            if (dist[u] + w < dist[v]) {
                dist[v] = dist[u] + w;
                pq.offer(new int[]{dist[v], v});
            }
        }
    }
    return dist;
}
```

## Topological Sort — ordering tasks with dependencies
```java
// A topological order lists nodes so that every directed edge u→v
// has u BEFORE v in the list.  Only possible on DAGs (no cycles).
//
// KAHN'S ALGORITHM (BFS-based — intuitive)
// Think of it like peeling an onion: remove all nodes with no incoming
// dependencies first, which exposes the next 'layer' of ready tasks.
List<Integer> topoSortKahn(List<List<Integer>> adj, int n) {
    int[] inDegree = new int[n];
    for (int u = 0; u < n; u++)
        for (int v : adj.get(u)) inDegree[v]++;
    Queue<Integer> q = new ArrayDeque<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) if (inDegree[i] == 0) q.offer(i);
    List<Integer> order = new ArrayList<>();
    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        int u = q.poll();
        order.add(u);
        for (int v : adj.get(u)) if (--inDegree[v] == 0) q.offer(v);
    }
    return order.size() == n ? order : Collections.emptyList(); // empty = cycle detected
}
```

## Topological Sort — DFS post-order reversal
```java
// DFS topo: visit all dependencies FIRST, then push current node to stack.
// Reverse the stack at the end → topological order.
// Why? Post-order means 'I'm done with everything that depends on me first.'
void dfsTopoSort(List<List<Integer>> adj, int u, boolean[] vis, Deque<Integer> stack) {
    vis[u] = true;
    for (int v : adj.get(u)) if (!vis[v]) dfsTopoSort(adj, v, vis, stack);
    stack.push(u);  // push AFTER all descendants are done
}
```

## Bellman-Ford — handles negative weights
```java
// Relax ALL edges V-1 times. Each pass can extend shortest paths by one more hop.
// Run one more pass: if any distance still improves → negative cycle exists.
//
// Mental model: imagine water slowly finding its lowest level —
// it takes at most V-1 steps to propagate cheapest costs across V nodes.
int[] bellmanFord(int n, int[][] edges, int src) {  // edges: [u, v, weight]
    int[] dist = new int[n];
    Arrays.fill(dist, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
    dist[src] = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)           // V-1 relaxation passes
        for (int[] e : edges)
            if (dist[e[0]] != Integer.MAX_VALUE && dist[e[0]] + e[2] < dist[e[1]])
                dist[e[1]] = dist[e[0]] + e[2];
    // V-th pass: detect negative cycle
    for (int[] e : edges)
        if (dist[e[0]] != Integer.MAX_VALUE && dist[e[0]] + e[2] < dist[e[1]])
            return null;  // negative cycle
    return dist;
}
```

## Minimum Spanning Tree — cheapest connected backbone
```java
// MST = subset of edges connecting ALL vertices with minimum total weight, no cycles.
//
// KRUSKAL'S (sort edges, use Union-Find to avoid cycles):
// Picture: sort all roads by cost, greedily add cheapest that don't form a loop.
//
// PRIM'S (grow one tree using a min-heap — similar to Dijkstra):
// Picture: start at any node, always add the cheapest edge that connects
// a NEW node to the already-grown tree.
//
// Kruskal outline:
Arrays.sort(edges, Comparator.comparingInt(e -> e[2]));
UnionFind uf = new UnionFind(n);
int mstWeight = 0;
for (int[] e : edges) {
    if (uf.union(e[0], e[1])) {   // only add if it doesn't form a cycle
        mstWeight += e[2];
    }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Using Dijkstra on a graph with negative edge weights — it gives wrong answers; use Bellman-Ford instead
- Not skipping stale heap entries in Dijkstra (d > dist[u] check) — causes redundant processing
- Topological sort on a graph with a cycle — Kahn's detects this (output size < n); plain DFS topo does not detect it automatically
- Bellman-Ford: running only V-2 relaxation passes (need exactly V-1)
- MST vs shortest path: MST minimises total edge weight tree-wide; Dijkstra minimises distance from one source — they are different problems

## Connections
- **Heaps**: Dijkstra needs a min-heap; Prim's MST also uses one
- **Graphs BFS/DFS**: Kahn's topo sort is BFS on a DAG; DFS topo uses post-order
- **Union-Find**: Kruskal's MST uses Union-Find for O(α(n)) cycle detection
- **DP**: Bellman-Ford and Floyd-Warshall are essentially DP on graphs

